INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3700','letter','1780-07-22','Newport','RI','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','The enemy are doing what they ought to do. Graves, immediately after having joined Arbuthnot, comes to cruise before us with nine or ten ships of the line, five frigates, and four other small vessels.','ltr_cdr3700.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3701','letter','1782-02-27','Williamsburg','VA','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','The legion de Lauzun by this time must be arrived at Charlotte Court-House. It will be needful that it stay there some time, because the men are almost quite naked','ltr_cdr3701.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3702','letter','1782-07-17','Philadelphia','PA','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','I had the honor to write to your Excellency that, at my departure from York in Virginia, I would leave in that place a detachment of four hundred French troops, which were to he joined by a corps of the Virginian militia','ltr_cdr3702.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3703','letter','1782-09-07','Princeton','NJ','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','The news which I have here of the British fleet, are that Admiral Pigot is got into New York with very few ships, himself in a bad state of health, and that Admiral Hood, with the greatest part of the fleet, has sailed for Halifax.','ltr_cdr3703.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3704','letter','1782-10-30','Hartford','CT','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','I received a letter from M. de Yaudreuil, saying that he is sorry to have appointed the 8th of next month for my arrival with my troops at Boston, because the men-of-war at Portsmouth are not yet ready','ltr_cdr3704.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3705','letter','1782-02-05','Williamsburg','VA','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','As, by the intelligences I had from your Excellency, and those I got from the flag, it appears that the reenforcement from New York for Charleston does not exceed thirteen hundred men','ltr_cdr3705.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3706','letter','1782-06-08','Williamsburg','VA','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Captain of a flag, arrived yesterday from New York, assures that he had sailed with thirty-six transports, escorted by three ships of war, going to Charleston and Savannah. They are empty, and it is believed they are going to evacuate those places.','ltr_cdr3706.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_cdr3707','letter','1780-11-14','Newport','RI','US','Jean Baptiste','de Vimeur','','George','Washington','','individual','','If your Excellency does not find a moment to come and see this part of your army, I am afraid that the whole of it will desert, so great is their desire to see their General.','ltr_cdr3707.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
